tural and be easy to understand. Across different accents of English, speech timing and rhythm seem to differ, and unfamiliarity with an accent's timing intuitively seems to lead to trouble understanding it. Yet there is little research into this area. This project addresses three questions:&lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>How do accents differ in the timing patterns associated with particular word shapes?&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Is comprehension disrupted if the &amp;quot;wrong&amp;quot; timing pattern is heard for a given accent?&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>How do speakers of different accents adjust to one another's timing patterns in conversation?&lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>

&lt;p>The project looks at the accents of Glasgow, Buckie, Leeds, Cambridge, and at Bradford British Asian English. It investigates the fine details of timing in specific types of word, such as feeler, filler and feel a [bit ill]. Methodologies include phonetic analysis of both conversational and read speech, and perceptual experimentation. Results will be used to design further research on speech timing patterns, and ultimately to build collaboration with psychologists and neuroscientists in order to understand the kinds of mental 'clocks' people use to perceive speech.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-08-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>136666</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Launch of Communicative Rhythms in Brain and Behaviour</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Regional</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>828474C1-6CEA-4841-BFEA-61AD29D667B4</gtr:id><gtr:impact>We held a launch event for a special issue of Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B, entitled &amp;quot;Communicative rhythms in brain and behaviour&amp;quot; at the University of Glasgow on 25 November 2014. There were talks from Fred Cummins (&amp;quot;The two faces of rhythm&amp;quot;) and Nigel Fabb (&amp;quot;Poem, brain, speech, rhythm&amp;quot;) and a fascinating performance by sound poet Hannah Silva. Attendees were a highly interdisciplinary group of academics from several institutions across Scotland.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>56e0af68232b66.67456296</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme