We have since begun to develop a collaboration with one of the organisers of the conference.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-2078483348.78541852a9afd5c</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Other academic audiences (collaborators, peers etc.)</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2011</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>English as a Foreign Language (EFL) seminar</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Local</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>0682A1D5-C74D-487B-BCD7-2B31072DC483</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Non-native learners frequently struggle with the prosodic aspects of English, and the rhythms of Scottish accents differ dramatically from those of the widely-taught varieties Southern British or Mainstream American. It is interesting to explore how training in production and perception of the rhythms of an accent might help learners understand and be understood. In February 2012, we organised a half-day tutorial on rhythmic aspects of English as foreign language at the University of Glasgow. Around 20 international students at the University of Glasgow participated and feedback suggested they found the workshop very useful. This sparked an ongoing collaboration between the University of Glasgow and Micro-Phonics Ltd through an AHRC Collaborative Doctoral Award explores these issues further.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>56e0ae979443a9.81805255</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Postgraduate students</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.gla.ac.uk/schools/critical/research/fundedresearchprojects/rhythmsinscotland/</gtr:url><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>55827</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp